Text.Value: Hold very still, Miklaur - Krank's aim is much improved but still leaves something up to chance.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Gwen Lee] Custom anim of Micklaur shaking in fear with an apple on his head, while an animated armor aims based on Lorroakan's hand gesture.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: [scene] Lorroakan has an animated armour shooting an apple off a halfling's head The halfing is trembling in fear as Lorroakan directs the armour.
EditorData.NodeContext: [Wilson] for this line, make sure the 1st pose is exactly the same as HUM_M_Rig_SCENE_LOW_SorcerousSundries_Lorroakan_DirectArmour (ends at 8s)

Text.Value: I couldn't bring her to you even if I wanted to.
Reconsider.
The Nightsong. Where is it?
Answer now, or see what happens when fools misuse my valuable time.
Not quite the enthusiastic welcome I was hoping for.
What do you want with her?
I'll fetch her. I look forward to my reward.
I'm afraid the mighty Nightsong was no match for my magic. She's dead.
Is that meant to be some consolation? She - it - was the key to my immortality.
It's quite simple. Bring the Nightsong here, and collect your reward.
Much as it pleases me to cause an archmage's tantrum, let us be sure we are ready to weather it - yes?
You know I seek the Nightsong. Do you have it or not?
Do as I say, and you'll be rewarded beyond imagination. Fail, and you give up the prize to the next motivated mercenary to encounter my contract.
I seek a certain rare tome - concerning Karsus.
We should kill this petulant wizard on our own terms, and allow Nightsong the pleasure of taking his head. Do not provoke him.
You must be the wizard Lorroakan.
I have.
She's been buried. Ended. Taken down. Offed. She's dead.
And me mine.
Ha! Betraying so quickly? Be careful your backstabbing arm doesn't get tired.
Leave me to my ruminations.
I can take my answers from your corpse if you prefer. A surprising number of people are more forthcoming dead than alive.
I know where she is. I might even be willing to tell you.
You would betray Dame Aylin? Be you faithless, or simply foolish?
I'll go fetch her. I look forward to my reward.
Karsus found that out the hard way, and those wonderful flying cities of yore were grounded in a most violent manner. His hubris undid him.
I see no Nightsong. Surely you wouldn't have entered my tower without the Nightsong in hand. Surely my worthless apprentice wouldn't have allowed you to waste my time.
Dame Aylin is going to want to kick this guy's arse herself. Believe me.
Well don't stand on ceremony - out with it.
You'll have more gratitude than you know how to count once the Nightsong is in my hands. Do you have it or not?
Alas. I've paid for a good deal of very privileged information. Now I await the results of the generous contract I've commissioned.
I'm sorry to tell you, but she's dead. Run through with a Sharran spear.
Then again, who will clean the mangled mess from my floor? So I'll ask again.
I can see you're in no place to have a civilised conversation. Return when an iota of sense has returned to you.
What's that? I didn't quite catch the words, but the insolent tone was clear enough.

EditorData.NodeContext: Mockingly - he doesn't believe Gale for an instant

Text.Value: The Crown of Karsus? Nonsense - even if it still existed, you couldn't possibly handle its power -
Just smile and nod. We'll decide at our own leisure, not his.
How exhausting it is, interacting with inferior minds and their vulgar motivations.
Beautiful, isn't it? Worth more than your life, too. I bought it from a Calishite warlock with very little of his soul left to him.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Gwen Lee] Please reuse HUM_M_Rig_DFLT_SCENE_Hag_Hagspawn_ResurrectHusband_ProduceWand_Player, but mirror the animation for Lorroakan.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: |He pulls out a wand and raises it for the player to admire.

Text.Value: It didn't work out for poor Ketheric, did it? He was a fool. A desperate mercenary who whored out his soul to whichever god flattered him.
Nothing at all, friend. I was merely admiring your ambition.
The wizard's a veritable geyser of rage. Provoke him, and he'll erupt.
Someone who might slip into your camp at any moment, or harry you through street and inn until you're run ragged and surrender.
Impossible, I daresay. Something so... unstable can scarcely exist as anything greater than a minute fragment.
A clever contraption. Let me guess: like Ketheric Thorm before you, you wish to become immortal.
We shall see, won't we?
The choice is yours, but make no mistake: I always get what I want.
I'm my own man. I make my own choices.
Hm. We have a visitor. At ease. Miklaur - you may go.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Gwen Lee] Lorroakan notices the player and stops his hand gesture, gives a head roll in a sour mood and calls off the armor's action with snapping the book.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: [scene] He gestures for the armour to lower the bow and for the halfling to leave. Krank lowers bow, Micklaur leaves.
EditorData.NodeContext:
Spots player and sours instantly. 
[Wilson] On Lorrokan part, at the very start have him hold like a beat then proceed with the line.

Text.Value: I serve no god but that which stares back at me in the mirror.
Why do you want her so badly?
She isn't an it.
Quick to hand someone over, aren't you?
Please - you can't liberate Aylin from one master only to chain her to another.
A clever contraption. Let me guess: like Ketheric Thorm before you, you wish to become immortal.
I've seen her - she was trapped by Ketheric Thorm. I left her there.
Surrendering a powerful ally to this preening wizard does not seem wise.
She was a Selnite held by Sharrans. Her death was inevitable.
First Ketheric and now you. I thought wizards were supposed to be the smart ones?
Ah. So it is you. Mystra's discarded lapdog. And now you think your bark is cause to make me tremble.
Good. Then you'll have no trouble fulfilling the contract to bring the Nightsong here.
Let him chase his prize if he wishes. We know of an even greater one that he is blind to - the Crown.
My - could it be? Gale of Waterdeep, here in my tower. I'm surprised you dare show your face after Mystra cast you on the scrap heap.
That's an awful fate. I won't subject my friend to it.
You aren't the only one who knows what's on offer for the Nightsong's retrieval. Consider carefully whether you'd like to see your fortune in someone else's hands.
Ambitious wizards and vast power can be a dangerous mix. Careful what you share with him.
Pity. Then again, perhaps word of your agonising death will draw your little friend to me.
Dead?! That cannot be. She - it - is immortal. A god!
Not anymore, thanks to me.
There is no need for me to bark. My actions will speak for themselves, in time.

EditorData.NodeContext: He does believe it, but he's blustering now

Text.Value: Choose your next words carefully, friend. They determine the length of your very life.
She must be an ally for you to try to mislead me. Bring her to me, and I'll forgive this momentary lapse of character.
I have little affection for Nightsong, but I would have less for you if you gave her up without a fight.
Your terrible tidings have cost me everything - my grand design, dashed to ruins.
You can get very rich along the way, or let someone else take what's rightfully yours. Choose wisely.
Explain yourself.
This always happens to me!

EditorData.NodeContext: The charisma fails; being a big brat

Text.Value: Once we acquire it, your ambitions will be dwarfed. I will be able to stand against Mystra, and wrest her powers from her. For the betterment of all.
Leave.
You have a job to do. So do it - quickly.
I acquired the 'The Annals of Karsus' from your bookseller. Did anything strike you as... unusual?
The Nightsong will be put to a grand purpose: equalising man and god. Whoever helps me attain that which I seek will be greatly rewarded.
You left her there?! Then go retrieve her, you imbecile. Or it will cost you a world of riches so vast you cannot even comprehend the loss.
The choice is yours: fortune or imminent death. I know you'll choose wisely.
Aylin is a friend - to whom we owe our lives, I would remind you.

EditorData.logicalname: No Gale inclusion, coming from HasMet

Text.Value: So you're the great wizard Lorroakan? I see your reputation is well earned...
'Her'. Fascinating. You've been to Shar's temple, haven't you? To the Shadowfell?
Bring me what I seek - and quickly - or do not come back. Ever.
Perhaps it was indeed wise to dissuade me from the Crown of Karsus - a jumped-up wizard drunk on promises of power is not enviable company.
She deserves better than to fall into his clutches. I owe her, in a sense.
You will bring me the Nightsong. Won't you?
I regret to inform you the Nightsong is no more - killed in the Sharran temple where she was held.
Netherese magic - could it be that a source of it - a significant source - still exists?
Then go - act. I'll open a fine vintage in your name, once word of your failure reaches me.
We can't do that - not after the lengths I already went through with her.
Get out of my face now.
You can go now. Before I lose my temper.
You broke Dame Aylin's shackles once before. Do not help this one to forge new ones for her.
Smile and nod.

EditorData.logicalname: Lae'zel told the player to smile and nod.

Text.Value: That was more than he strictly needed to know. You're not intending to surrender her over to him, are you...?

EditorData.logicalname: LOGICAL NODE - Not coming from hasmet

Text.Value: I know nothing. I swear it.
Tell me - and choose your next words carefully - where is she now?
*His suspicions confirmed, his curiosity settles into a sneer - he has seen through Gale's disguise.*
That's none of your business.
Pitying, not insolent. You chase one power without knowing an even greater one lies within my reach - the Crown of Karsus.
You speak as though you've seen the Nightsong yourself.
No more so than the rest of the volatile tomes in Tolna's collection. I had her keep them under lock and key to avoid any mishaps.
He would seek the power of gods for the pettiest of reasons - his own gratification. At least I seek them for the better of all.
Do not return without my prize. Do you hear me? Good day.
But enough of dusty history - I look to the future.
All right, Krank. Ready, aim -

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Gwen Lee] Micklaur still shaking in fear, the animated armor pulls the bow more and more to it's climax. Lorroakan's hand gestures also reaches a climax.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: [scene] The animated armour raises the bow and aims it at the halfling's head, drawing the string.
EditorData.NodeContext: [Wilson] on Lorrokan part, would want him to have a gesture on his left hand when he says"Krank ready, aim" and hold the last pose sligtly longer around 2 beats.

Text.Value: A shame to wizardry, this one. Still, we should exercise caution.
I'll think about it.
First Ketheric, now you - there are easier ways to achieve immortality, you know.
It can bind a celestial to the wearer's service with a snap of the fingers.
We're all very impressed by your loyalty, but have we considered not aggravating the incredibly powerful archmage?
*Barely a breath of confusion, before he sees you through your borrowed guise.*
You heard me. The answer is no.
I do admire your directness, though. Quick and to the point.
'Equalising man and god'. Quite the lofty ambition.
I've always dreamt of immortality. Your plan is quite clever.
I will admit I have not listened to a single thing the ginger wizard has said. But I do not like the way he says it.
So was it you who picked up Nightsong's trail? I suppose you still have some talents, even if you are damaged goods. Where is it?
What's that? I didn't quite catch the words, but your tone was clear enough.
I'll tell her to come here - just to give her the satisfaction of ripping you to shreds.
I might tell you. But there is another matter I wished to ask you about.
I do. And I can hand her over, for the right price.
I see no Nightsong. Surely you wouldn't have entered my tower without the Nightsong in hand. Surely you wouldn't have wasted my time.
Do you still pine for her? Run around trying to impress her, in the hope she'll take you back?
You don't know what you've done. And you never will.
How can this be - how can this be?! SHIT!

EditorData.NodeContext: He's just learned Nightsong is dead and is upset.

Text.Value: Yes, sir.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: [scene] Krank is trying to balance an apple on his head

Text.Value: I'll tell her to come here - just to give her the satisfaction of ripping you to shreds.
Of course not. But perhaps, after enough lifetimes, I might make a start of it.
Nothing, friend. Just a little trapped wind - I'm sure you understand.
Perhaps you could not. But Netheril's power is in my blood, and Mystra? I know her in ways that most mortals can only dream of.
And the Nightsong? Speak true, now, for I detest a liar.
Why do you want her so badly?
I'm growing tired of this repartee, my friend. Let us cut to the chase.
You seem to know a great deal about her. Bring her to me, and I'll forgive your little fib about her fate.
You keep telling yourself that.
Myrmidons - imperatum!
Leave.
And you must have an answer to my request - if you want to keep your head, of course. The Nightsong. Do you have it or not?
'Equalising man and god' - noble words cannot hide a selfish intent, wizard.
Shht! Don't tell him!

EditorData.NodeContext: To player, urgently, warning them not to tell this villaiin anything else incriminating. A little exasperated like 'shouldn't you know better?'

Text.Value: You're quite in luck, then - see Tolna downstairs. One such tome is amongst our rarest books.
Attack.
I intend to achieve greatness. And I intend to do it for a long, long, long time.
Ah. I believe I recognise you. Gale of Waterdeep. Mystra's discarded lapdog, reduced to trailing after some adventurer. How you have fallen.
You better not be planning on giving her up. Not after everything she's been through.

EditorData.NodeContext: A warning to the player. And projecting a little wrt her own situation.

Text.Value: Why tell him anything of Dame Aylin? Surely you do not intend to betray her...?
You must be the wizard Lorroakan. I've heard a great deal about you.
You stand in the presence of Gale of Waterdeep, Lorroakan. Mind your tongue.
'She'. Then you do know her. You've been to Shar's temple. To the Shadowfell. You've looked upon the Nightsong's face.
I'm glad you will not surrender an ally, but we should still be cautious around this one.

EditorData.NodeContext: 'this one' being lorroakan, who is asking the player to betray an ally to him

Text.Value: There is more to divinity than lifespan. Ensnaring an immortal won't make you a god.
Have it your way. I'll bring her here.
I'll consider your request.
You would betray Dame Aylin? Be you faithless, or simply foolish?
I'll do no such thing.
Ach! Worthless. Leave, then. And do not return unless you bring the Nightsong in tow. It's not too late for you to become very rich. But you'll have to earn it.
You'd give up her location, just like that? You're not actually considering betraying her, are you...?
Ha! Betraying so quickly? Be careful your backstabbing arm doesn't get tired.
You're an arrogant fool. Immortality alone does not make a god.
Mark my words: the Nightsong is mine. With or without your help, she will ascend to her grand fate here, in this tower.
Would you hand her over to have her wings pulled off by this self-inflated wretch?
'Clever' doesn't begin to describe it. What I seek is the greatest ambition possible: to defy the ultimate limitation, transcend the fate that awaits us all.
Good. I was growing scared for you. The last person who disappointed me is suffering for it still.

*There is only one man who would make such a brazen claim about Mystra. His suspicions confirmed, Lorroakan's curiosity settles into a sneer - this is Gale of Waterdeep. However else he might appear.*
What do you want with her?
Tut tut, now. I do detest a liar.
Are you serious? Surely you won't hand Dame Aylin over to him.
Finally. I've been waiting for someone with any measure of wits to heed my clarion call.
And this? This can keep her in place. Forever.

EditorData.AnimationTags: [Gwen Lee] HUM_M_Rig_DFLT_SCENE_Hag_Hagspawn_ResurrectHusband_StowWand_Player can be reused for stowing away the wand. As for the gesture, please reuse HUM_M_Rig_DFLT_CINE_ArmsOutToSide_StandR_02. Might have to tweak the speed sligthly for it but it should work.
EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: He gestures to the spell circle on the ground - same as the one Ketheric used used to bind Nightsong in Act 2

Text.Value: Thanks for revealing your plan. I look forward to watching Dame Aylin rip you to shreds.
Be careful what you wish for. She'll eat you alive.
When I succeed, I may look favourably upon you. If you are a friend along the way, that is.
Binding the Nightsong forever... How unoriginal. Need I recite the tale of Ketheric Thorm?

Synopsis: Lorroakan's initial dialog with the player in Ramazith's tower, where he plans to have Nightsong imprisoned like Ketheric had. He will ask the player to deliver her to him.
